<br>
I admit, you can nudge your emotions, but not subborn, and because your emotions retain a certain independent freedom so must your moral decisions.  Logic and reason cannot solve all problems, though crying about things in the name of &quot;humanity&quot; &lt;i&gt;is&lt;/i&gt; just as absurd.  Objectivism breaks down in that it attempts to unravel human interaction using linear and logical methods that are trying to explain things that may or may not be linear or logical.  <br>
<br>
Definition of &quot;human life&quot; for example in terms of abortion rights.  When the right of an individual begins is a very moral, subjective decision.  I believe that until a baby is born it is part of its mother and her property in a legal manner to do with as she wants.  This is not because I understand the definition any better than any other person but simply because I have made a choice.  <br>
<br>
You would argue that it is my reason that makes this choice, and yes, it does, but reason does not always lead to the same conclusion.  Rand never allowed for differing viewpoints and there are a lot of times in her life, some quite dramatic, where she was ruthless with opposition that claimed the use of reason.  Note the schism between Rand and Brandon, for example.  <br>
<br>
In the end her philosophy is a good general outlook and absolutely must be taken into account when setting down the basics of human interaction, the surface interactions between people, but they absoutely cannot and should not be applied to deeper internal matters.  Yes, the sense of self is paramount and a priori to all other facets of an individual, but the self is not where the story ends. <br>
<br>
