<br>
Whether you or I like it or not the very definitions of the words we use have both denotative as well as connotative meanings.  Obviously, as connotations change words change their implied meanings, but even denotative meanings can be changed over time.  Denotation is created only when a particular definition is authorized by religion or a nation-state.  <br>
<br>
Thus, what is or is not torture has been argued ever since the rennaisance.  Even terms like torture, nation, religion, culture and humanity were created out of the struggle to define nation versus religion.  This relatively recent concept of seperation of church and state itself is still only as true as we allow it.  Obviously there are many bastions of religion still present in the basis of our government, but we still call it a seperation of church and state.<br>
<br>
